<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06255566 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06255566 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Linda Harris  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A parade celebrating Mexico's independence from Spain will wind throughdowntown San Jose on Sunday.;   The parade, part of the Fiestas Patrias 1991!celebration, starts at 10 a.m. at Ninth and East Santa Clara streets and endsat Plaza Park. The celebration continues in the park until 5 p.m.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PARADE TO CELEBRATE MEXICAN REBELLION  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  In Brief; Also ran in EX4/3; SETTING THE RECORD STRAIGHT (publ. 9/12/91, pg.2B); Because of a reporting error, the day of the 15th annual Almaden Art andWine Festival was incorrect in some editions of Wednesday's Extra sections.The event will be from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. Sunday at Parma Park, next to theAlmaden Community Center, 6445 Camden Ave. in San Jose.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Mexican Independence Day, Sept. 16, commemorates the 1810 call forrebellion of Father Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla.;   The parade and celebrationare sponsored by the Mercury News and the American GI Forum-San Jose chapter.;CONTACT: This week is National CONTACT Week. CONTACT USA, a national networkof telephone help line and crisis intervention centers, is taking this week tocall attention to its 24-hour help line.;   Locally, CONTACT-Santa ClaraCounty responded to 18,822 calls last year, an increase of 18 percent morethan the previous year, according to Barbara Joachim, executive director. Thelocal crisis line is (408) 279-8228.;   This week also gives CONTACT a chanceto recruit volunteers to handle the calls.;   Volunteers receive 50 hours ofclassroom training followed by 16 hours of apprenticeship on the phones.;  For information on becoming a volunteer, call (408) 279-8228.; NEW REGISTRAR:Linda S. Harris has been appointed registrar of Evergreen Valley College.;   Harris, who began her job July 29, worked at San Jose State University invarious positions, including assistant director of records.;   She receivedher bachelor's degree in social science from SJS and has received theuniversity's Woman of Achievement Recognition Award.; REDISTRICTING: Thepublic has two upcoming opportunities to discuss changing the boundaries ofSan Jose City Council districts.;   A redistricting public hearing isscheduled for 7 p.m. Thursday at the Pioneer High School cafeteria, 1290Blossom Hill Road.;   Another hearing is scheduled for Sept. 19 at 7 p.m. inthe San Jose City Council Chambers, 801 N. First St.;   After every federalcensus, the city is required to establish new boundaries to reflect thedemographic changes of the previous decade. These hearings are part of thatprocess.;   Copies of the Redistricting Advisory Commission's recommended mapas well as maps submitted by members of the commission will be available atthe hearings. Anyone wishing to submit a proposal needs to bring copies forthe public.; ART, WINE: The 15th annual Almaden Art and Wine Festival willkick off at 10 a.m. Saturday at Parma Park, next to the Almaden CommunityCenter, 6445 Camden Ave. in San Jose.;   Sponsored by the Almaden ValleyWomen's Club, the event offers works of 130 artists and crafts people. Inaddition to wine, stout and ale also will be offered for tasting. Food boothsalso will be available.;   Entertainment will be provided by the Joe SharinoBand, which plays 1950s and '60s music, and also from other local bands --Resounding Joy, Zamar and Ike and the Cold Bloods.;   This year, child carewill be available at Simonds School near the festival.;   Proceeds from theevent will support such projects as Almaden area schools, libraries and theAlmaden Counseling Center.; The Almaden Valley Women's Club is a 26-year-oldnon-profit organization.; EVC GRANT: Evergreen Valley College's NursingProgram last month received a $10,000 grant from the New York-based HeleneFuld Health Trust, for what the college describes as &quot;interactive&quot; videoequipment, software and other computer components for the program's computerlab.;   The equipment is to aid instructors in training a population in whichEnglish as a Second Language students make up a third of the nursing programenrollment, according to the college.;   In addition, more than half theprogram's students are estimated to come from minority-group backgrounds.;  More information on the EVC nursing program is available by calling (408)270-6448.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Compiled by E. Mark Moreno  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910911  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  683  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, September 11, 199100255566,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>